  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c1e3b5d7f9a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b1d3f5a7c9e2b4d6f8a1c3e5b7d9",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is a commercially validated finite element solver with documented V&V procedures. The modeling team followed an established quality management plan including version control, peer review of scripts, and regression testing against benchmark problems. Achieved Gradation 3 through independent code review and documented test suite execution."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the linear elastic constitutive model and contact formulation. Convergence of the numerical solution to the analytical benchmark was confirmed at the expected theoretical rate, satisfying Gradation 2 requirements for this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was conducted on the pedicle screw shank and rod assembly. The Richardson extrapolation-based Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for construct stiffness was 0.8%, and for yield force was 1.1%, both well below the 5% threshold. The production mesh (approximately 420,000 elements, predominantly C3D8I) was selected at the fine level, achieving Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out of this credibility assessment on the basis that the Ansys Mechanical implicit solver employs a direct sparse solver (SPARSE) with double-precision arithmetic throughout. For the linear elastic regime governing the QoIs of interest (stiffness, yield force), the system of equations is well-conditioned (condition number < 1e6 as confirmed by solver diagnostics), and iterative convergence is not applicable. The direct solver produces a solution to machine precision for each load step, making residual solver error negligibly small relative to other uncertainty sources (discretization, material input variability). This scope-out is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.4 guidance that factors demonstrably non-influential to total simulation uncertainty may be excluded with documented justification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out because the simulation workflow is executed exclusively by the FDA OSEL computational mechanics team under a controlled, documented simulation governance framework. The analysis procedure is codified in a validated simulation protocol (SOP-FEA-2022-04) that has undergone independent technical review. All model setup steps — including boundary condition application, material assignment, contact definition, and load application — are scripted in Ansys APDL macros subject to version control and peer review, eliminating ad-hoc manual entry. The risk of consequential operator error is therefore assessed as negligible, and the factor does not contribute meaningfully to the overall credibility gap. This exclusion is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.4 and is documented in the simulation governance record (https://uofa.net/nagaraja/governance/sop-fea-2022-04)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-gradation3",
      "rationale": "The model employs a linear elastic, isotropic constitutive law for Ti-6Al-4V components, which is appropriate for the pre-yield regime of interest. The ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry is represented explicitly. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) is applied at screw-rod interfaces based on published tribological data. Model form assumptions were evaluated against the experimental force-displacement curves; the linear elastic regime prediction falls within 5% of experimental mean for all three QoIs, supporting Gradation 3 adequacy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E=114 GPa, nu=0.33 for Ti-6Al-4V) were sourced from ASTM F136 certified material certificates for the specific lot used in bench testing. Geometric dimensions were taken from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test articles (n=3 screws, n=3 rods). Torque-preload on the set screw was measured with a calibrated torque wrench and applied as an equivalent pretension in the model. Input uncertainty was propagated via a Monte Carlo analysis (N=1000 samples) confirming that QoI sensitivity to input variability is within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Eleven (N=11) non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6; Lab 2: n=5). All constructs were manufactured from the same production lot, with dimensional conformance verified by CMM prior to testing. The sample size is sufficient to characterize inter-specimen variability and compute experimental uncertainty for E/uval comparison, satisfying Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 prescribed conditions (ambient temperature, quasi-static loading rate of 5 mm/min, standard fixture geometry). Only one test condition was evaluated; no variation in loading rate, temperature, or fixture offset was explored. This limits the factor to Gradation 1, which is below the required Gradation 2. This gap is acknowledged in the decision record and accepted given that ASTM F1717 is a standardized protocol with fixed conditions, the COU is limited to this specific test configuration, and the single-condition limitation is consistent with regulatory precedent for 510(k) submissions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/equivalency-inputs-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The FEA model inputs were reconciled against the as-tested experimental conditions through a formal input equivalency review. Boundary conditions (fixture pin locations, loading axis alignment) were set to match the physical test setup as documented in the laboratory test reports. Material property values used in the model were drawn from the same material certificates as the tested hardware. No surrogate or assumed input values were required, confirming Gradation 2 equivalency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the E/uval metric per ASME V&V 40-2018. For construct stiffness: E/uval = 0.84 (< 1.96 acceptance bound, percent difference = 3.2%). For yield force: E/uval = 1.21 (< 1.96, percent difference = 6.8%). For force at 40 mm displacement: E/uval = 1.47 (< 1.96, percent difference = 8.9%). All three QoIs satisfy both the 10% percent-difference criterion and the E/uval < 1.96 criterion, achieving Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly relevant to the clinical question of construct mechanical integrity under physiological bending loads. These QoIs are identical between the validation activity and the intended submission use, confirming Gradation 2 relevance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-gradation3",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same ASTM F1717 test configuration, the same loading modality (compression-bending), and the same FEA modeling framework used for the submission prediction. The validation constructs are from the same production lot as the submission device. No extrapolation in geometry, material, loading, or modeling approach is required, supporting Gradation 3 validation relevance."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending) is accepted at Medium assurance level. Eleven of thirteen V&V 40 factors are formally assessed; two factors (Numerical solver error, Use error) are scoped out with documented rationale establishing their negligible contribution to total simulation uncertainty. Of the eleven assessed factors, ten meet or exceed their required credibility level. One factor — Test conditions — achieves Gradation 1 against a required Gradation 2, reflecting that ASTM F1717 prescribes a single standardized test condition. This gap is accepted because: (1) the COU is explicitly bounded to the F1717 standard configuration; (2) the single-condition limitation is inherent to the standard and is consistent with FDA regulatory precedent for 510(k) submissions of spinal implants; and (3) the quantitative output comparison (E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; maximum percent difference 8.9%) provides direct empirical evidence that the model is fit for purpose within the stated COU. The provenance chain is complete: experimental data from two independent laboratories (N=11) is linked to validation results with documented uncertainty quantification, and all model inputs are traceable to calibrated measurements and certified material data. The overall evidence base supports a Medium assurance conclusion, commensurate with the Medium model risk level and Medium decision consequence.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
